A Republican Strategy to Face Obama’s Re-Election
Republicans’ leaders justify their policies with the need to fight election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth by affirming that election fraud in the U.S. is less common than the number of people killed by lightning strikes.
Republicans’ lawyers have reported only 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is for sure: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for running the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that complicate the procedure for registration or appointment.
This phenomenon has gained in importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives could be registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of electoral law in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court act exists.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state has asked voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana’s law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted draft laws in 34 states that force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new voters do not have such an ID in 2012.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to get the required ID.
Young people, minorities and people with low incomes are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are seen as voters who increasingly vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state has asked for proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
It is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have promoted laws in eight states in 2011 that abolished voter registration on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns for voter registration in the 2004 general elections helped to register about 10 million citizens.
As a result of the measures adopted since 2009, the proportion of new voters registered in 2010 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they accounted for only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of the voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passing of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws that require the display of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the states decisive for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required by the Electoral Men’s Committee to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these amendments to the legislation on the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is for sure: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Prostate cancer early detection: should the test be done or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes showed incorrect results, with false negative or even false positive results that lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
