Another study, this time from Europe, came to the conclusion that there is a difference in the mortality of patients with and without early detection.
This study has also shown that after 12 years of follow-up, the likelihood of formation of metastases is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection has been performed.
Therefore, I recommend the test from the age of 50 or 40 if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
There is also a higher risk for African-American men.
The most important thing is to make the right decision once a cancer has been detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient needs to be made really understandable about the extent of the risk of his cancer by showing him the possible options where prostate cancer can remain untreated if it does not affect the quality of life in the long term, and in these cases, he is more likely to opt for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer do not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to their lives.
They are suggested to be actively monitored and to be treated as the disease progresses.
With increasing accuracy, the criteria for a decision are determined, who should be treated and who should not be treated.
That is why I recommend conducting the test.
Most important, however, is to talk to his doctor to determine whether he should be performed or not.
