The Higgs boson analyzed
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has sparked a bit of excitement last summer, and for good reason.
It is indeed believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "at least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still data missing to be completely sure about it.
However, if we assume that it is actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of being fooled, and we look at what it is about.
There is an inevitable law in this world, which means that two objects cannot be present in the same place at the same time.
It’s not possible to violate this rule – and don’t try it too hard as you’ll hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to them: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state", this "state" being largely composed of some of its properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and politely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, an evil band of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
According to The Particle Adventure website, these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we won’t treat here and the “power particles” by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "message" of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at this exact location, approximately like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disorder" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of power".
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" so that this boson shows up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the exciter must achieve very high energies, a bit comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be marred by a very large rock.
This is why a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never keep by itself at the refrigerator.
And similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon by the way) have no mass.
For what can all these research be "good," asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to carefully investigate any deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has great defects, as it does not provide an explanation for the gravity (ups!) and dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Impacts
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous-stroke laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was at first seen as a "laboratory".
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves as an “eye” for all digital cameras worldwide and has earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize for Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With her committee on "Death in Dignity", Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed soon, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, there is still much to do in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this in more detail.
A few weeks ago Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
“However, it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he says.
The disease does its job: an immense weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to be resigned to help with the meal.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
“In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing while standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
“That depends on the person’s ability to take a step back,” he notes.
According to several people who work in palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called “healing” care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and through suffocation".
But because of the illness, I really got to know my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
"I don't have any wishes in life anymore," she says, before she accepts to put on a mask that helps her breathe.
In the next few days, she still expects her son to come from Italy.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers offer personal care and assistance in food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 people.
This is very little, considering that one day we will all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
A mouth care with brandy or pepsi is granted to the dying person as desired.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died over the course of the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the foot of the deceased.
“We are helping relatives and patients alike,” says Nathalie Savard, the care director.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois there is no day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years old, who enjoys the last family gathering in the yard and is well supported by his pillow while he is pushed to his honor, a young man of 36 years old, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, tragically dies after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years of age," Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their residence, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e., to care to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Montreal-wide Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
Precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec health care ensures that several doctors specialized in palliative care are concerned about the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting the move to death care.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without taking any measures to relieve her.
I fear that the patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst predictions, until the last day.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued a cumbersome chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she replied to me that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
She told me that I was in the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the caregivers for failing to do so after their pain has been alleviated by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care in pain treatment is not omnipotent.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Montreal Society of Domestic Palliative Care, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in the patient sleeping either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to sleep with me,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
