With 15,000 computers on the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After the price of Bitcoin reached a peak of $30 ($23) in June 2011, it dropped to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to traditional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to progress in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes also trade back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed every time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of the invoice book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public account book spread throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege to add this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "cracked."
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task gets 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
Bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to a hundred millionths, leaving a certain amount of room for manoeuvre.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites providing services to Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real money payment company and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others such as the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the billbook and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega closing sale" was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions, which are cheaper as a result.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by traders, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to provide an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are considered in favor of more horizontal systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to get through, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB's report provides for a reassessment of the various risks currently considered to be highly regarded in the event of a success of this currency.
