A constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever in terms of the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of his work.
Egypt has now been relying for almost two years on a provisional text that has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only created an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "put right with his feet".
On the part of its proponents, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to forgo their plan to explain to the Egyptians the text section by section.
For the president, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest rages across the country.
After confirmation in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohammed Mursi appears to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably.
Especially since the Egyptian people, with this recourse to a hasty vote, are placed an ultimatum: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals have not complied with the request.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away, believing that they have not been able to bring their views to light.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
To achieve the quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly unanimously adopted.
By the way, the commentators found it amusing that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the constituent assembly was not going exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Beautifulness" answers the liberals, who see this only as a propaganda blow.
According to them, the Islamicization of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which recognises an advisory function of the University of Al-Azhar, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt’s specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because “the people who are asked for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the first signs of theocracy here.”
The concerns of the liberals are also fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
“There is currently no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who have been partially trained in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He concedes, however, that "there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
In particular, reference is made here to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide on it."
In addition to his religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticized for the far-reaching powers he grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not presented to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations have called for in defence of human rights.
The latter also share their fears about the text they consider to be freedom-threatening.
The facts of blasphemy are being maintained, and insults are now forbidden, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no more articles relate to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak out on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and an untouched nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons to visit Israel.
bowing in front of the holy places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all those who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the conversion of water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on the water, the sedation of the sea storm and fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the shrines are found in Jerusalem.
Here, believers take the path of suffering or the cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, in the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem is also the holiest place of the Jews - the lamentation wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave papers there with wishes that then come true.
Take a trip to the top
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hideout from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 A.D.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the mountaintop.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
In just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be made a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls of the Dead Sea found in rock caves in the Judean desert are kept, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There, the collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso will be exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bathers.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most gripping section is the memorial to the children, which was built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room, there is total darkness.
The stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do something for health
The three main recreation areas of Israel are located on the banks of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21°C and the air warms up to 23°C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed there all year round.
Incidentally, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salt content and thus even carries non-swimmers on the surface without any problems.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and medicinal sludge, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm stressed nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets hold the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route linking Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be the legend of all those who touch the walls of the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed today.
List of Tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
You prefer not to take the money in euros, but in dollars that can be easily changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get on the bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only metro line of the country with six stations that connects the lower city to the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the mode of transport, which includes transfers for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is at rest.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without dandruff and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with ham and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-fed cats that roam the streets comfortably and indecently.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don’t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
Bicycle rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, which corresponds to an increase of 51% compared to the comparison period in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the maintenance of the families remaining in the home.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every migrant worker must take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this rule applies only to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in retail.
However, over time, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
In doing so, one must not only take language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be proven for both obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The entire examination body will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of People's Friendship, the Moscow State University, the Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law came into force in the press: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
In particular, counter-speakers from the Migration Authority are concerned with reducing the number of forced labourers.
“Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers,” says Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency’s representation in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only an organized recruitment will 90% solve the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants encounter problems without a job, education, language skills and medical evaluation.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who, under the pretext of help, put him in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his own months without food and documents and spend 12 to 14 hours a day.
There are many complaints from our migrants.
“At home, the One will be promised to you, and upon arrival you will be cheated, their passports will be taken away, and you will not receive the promised pay,” confirmed the head of the head of the labor migration department of the Tajik Migration Agency, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't insult me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that not only do they not master the language of the target country, but they can hardly express themselves in their own language in writing.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable primary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
“You feel humiliated and inferior.”
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspects of the law.
Only migrants with legal status are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers continue to stay illegally in Russia.
"Really welcome" or "access for unauthorized persons prohibited"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to get an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly faked and we are not registered, and that is when cases of extortion arise.
“They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea,” Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Just don't shy away from the cost of wrong papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be faked.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
That’s more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this one costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased, both officials and civil rights activists agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered positions in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in crimes extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten the gun law for private gun owners.
The authorities are thus responding to the latest events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the shooting of Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Combating Corruption, Irina Jarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Weapons Act will be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - call on the authorities to distance themselves from "sensuous intensifications".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal justice, Wasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes were committed with the use of registered weapons over the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not stop criminals from serving on the black market.
According to the authors in Moscow, one can find any weapon for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who spent ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez said.
The second channel contains illegal weapons, which are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons that have been stolen from both the police’s arms chambers and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
In many military camps, explosions often occurred.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers are also making a contribution to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private armaments factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore squander the weapons under hand on the black market, for example in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a separate, sometimes artisan production there, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling,” the former military member explains.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in supplying the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, according to the investigators, come from the army and the law enforcement agencies.
Half of all the weapons on the black market are there because of the "debt of those responsible for their work with weapons," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict zones, 14% are based on thefts in the production of weapons, and 5% are from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun store who doesn’t want to be named, assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been bought by no one, as they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get the supplies in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, for example a TT-type pistol, is bought via a faucet.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
“The police, of course, know all about it and therefore, if they can’t comply with the crime detection plan, periodically conduct control purchases at dealers offering illegal weapons,” the sales consultant added.
"As in the luxury shop"
