"The brain can only be moderately overtaken"
The topic of expanded reality, popular among modern technology fans, has recently been commonly perceived by the lens of a special eyewear.
Google first presented a working model at its annual conference this summer, and in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed a patent.
In conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft lab in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, however, it becomes clear that the glasses for the company’s scientists were only a transit station.
It stimulates the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and create virtual free spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely remained stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to look ahead 5-10 years and anticipate the radical changes of this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are progressing, and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What do we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, much still takes place on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We try to change that, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We must release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much more easily.
And first of all, we should get rid of these messy virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overrated?
- It is certainly not the general purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform all those around you about their actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the field of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project where we experimented with short and short, rather than exuberant gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gestures and language.
- How's that?
- For example, we'd ask you to give me this spray can?
They say it and point it out at the same time.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can do at the time and what not?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on developing new sensor types that will allow us to more accurately capture reactions from people.
These can be laser sensors, for example, as they offer a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What are your demands from working with the Xbox Kinect sensors on modern cameras?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or anything else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the area of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixel itself, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
All current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work.
It is not only necessary to consider the resolution along the X and Y axis, but also along the Z axis.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The movements of man are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps, especially for gestures, are too little.
In our Redmond laboratory, Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of humans and machines.
For my work, I needed a device like this, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras may be able to solve the problem...
Or increase the problem, as more calculations would be needed.
It would be nice to have a flexible Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera inclinations to see how this helps us determine a position in three dimensions.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that with regard to the application of the technology of extended reality in everyday life, the glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand on the go, but I think the best option would be a "changing" extended reality where we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and they contain their strength (privates can only see you), but at the same time their weakness, because an expanded reality using glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
- Let’s imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point to: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that the expanded reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently using the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She takes great care of pressure!
However, there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is currently still as weak as if someone was breathing over the palms.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that affect the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Did you try to outsmart the brain?
Thinking that it feels what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we work on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), mobile platforms as well as large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately overtaken, and there are still many years of work ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so appealing to a researcher: on many topics, we are only at the beginning.
