Public funds managed by the districts and municipalities are subject to the control of the state accounting offices.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would like to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, Germany is often referred to as an example in some respects, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is it because the examiners are better?
This is certainly not the case, but as I said, I do not like such comparisons very much.
It should also be noted that those countries that are an example to us also have problems with this.
Otherwise, they wouldn’t have anything to do with our agency, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what was the significance of the amendment of the awarding law for your authority, do you already feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this novel is only in effect for a short time, it has not yet had an effect on our tests.
Since our controls take place later, a certain delay must be expected here.
To date, we are more likely to feel the effects in the preparatory phase of future controls - this is how we have introduced the new control tool "Identification of risks of inefficiency" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts are examined and analysed - here the changes will of course have an effect, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positively, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem can occur that the rules become “stricter” and can no longer be observed.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to an audit are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the effect that any non-compliance with the procurement law is equivalent to a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think that way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a form error that does not affect actual decision-making.
Such a system only puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
First of all, let’s say which path is not a good one.
The prime minister recently said that the ODS would not brighten the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system banned or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply come to the head of government, and the office of control, whose duty is now to control the law, can hinder its activity.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we do as if nothing were.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain operations - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, however, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely due to form errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be properly applied - and that is what I think we lack.
