<0xC5><0xA0>imon Ornest: At our concerts we want to collect positive energy
What do you think will happen in less than a month of the end of the world?
This is one of those disasters that we humans are so fond of.
With our band The Tap Tap, we’re more likely to make fun of it and say that we’re the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a national benefit event, which we have been planning for two years.
For this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, whose end is forecast for December 21st at 11:10 a.m.
On the day before, i.e. on December 20th, three concerts will take place in Prague, Brno and Ostrava at the same time from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is said to be about the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone around 12 hours ahead of us.
From whom does this idea come?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we once pass this world on to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, with which people can also support us through www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, together with other artists, has also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world entitled "The end of the world falls out".
Even today, the anthem is very popular on YouTube. Will it also sound on the benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, provided that everything works and the end of the world does not take place...
The hymn is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast live together in a live broadcast by Czech TV.
The lyrics of the hymn come from Tom<0xC3><0xA1><0xC5><0xA1> Han<0xC3><0xA1>k, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also sings Xindl X with...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and have fun with it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the accessible educational centre Studeo, where we have been working together with the association Tap at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute for six years.
The students of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, a separate building is to be built, into which we will then move in with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers appear.
What criteria did you choose?
We wanted to put together a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, support lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan B<0xC3><0xA1>rta, The Tap Tap Tap, Mari<0xC3><0xA1>n Bango and Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> Such<0xC3><0xBD> appear.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar “big events” planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and we will also prepare an interesting programme with interesting guests for this concert.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not exactly small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we must carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without any problems so far, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travels abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxemburg, London and other cities where everything works better than with us, we witnessed in Russia that in the East everything is still in its beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not suitable for disabled people, where it is still unusual if someone is in a wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even a matter of course that a wheelchair user is allowed in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also clubs that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we need to catch up with the developed countries?
There are a lot of things that we hang behind...
However, it should also be noted that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public space, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not quite common for a larger group of disabled people to participate actively in social events, in which we are a bit ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years: what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a supervisor at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in dealing with something intensely.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, among other things, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, L<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>, used to say, something got out of control (laughs).
However, the band only became known in recent years, or am I mistaken?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us, and we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and you can’t see it outward, your own performance doesn’t exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to EU funding, we can also afford good editors, high-quality equipment and etc.
Was it your goal to bring it so far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I have felt the potential to do things differently.
In the show business, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is looked at with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare to claim that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is of course pity; this is only natural...
But this pity is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full life if they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not only a step forward for them, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you cannot compromise on many things and you also have to demand a certain discipline.
I think this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have a rehearsal twice a week, have to complete preparation phases and spend a lot of time on concert trips, then the enthusiasm of many quickly fades away.
But that’s how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has 20 members.
How many of them have been there since the beginning of 1998?
Only one: L<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't prevent that.
Whoever has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
