Poland and Space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency at a Council of Ministers meeting of the Member States of the European Space Agency (ESA), making it the second member state from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, not always coming across understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
<0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, in 1934 for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s globally recognized contribution to the development of space travel was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925 a railway taxi was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or brake the drains.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered missiles.
The research was carried out by the Institute Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents handed down that the research had progressed to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, in the trade press, the design of a photoelectric hunting dragon by Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpedoa powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, its work was terminated from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on spaceflight appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Agency (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company takes place in 1954 in the November issue of the journal Problemy, in which four extensive articles on space travel are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time, there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was to be expected that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact, the PTA became a regular member in the fall of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests began in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w Desert with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another development stage should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The successor to the first type RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the take-off weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space with 0.4 liters of capacity, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight altitude was 37 km for all three types.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aviation, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth noting that Poland’s accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermazevsky became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek.
The repeal of the law on charitable works is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on non-profit works.
This decision sparked a lively discussion in the public eye.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberally oriented economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in a permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of work (rewards), there are price tensions.
This term is to be understood as a condition in which the manufacturer tries to compete in economic competition by importing cheap goods by "subsidising competition" in order to increase its market share and increase its profit.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to relocate their production abroad or buy cheaply there, or to abandon their business. The result is high unemployment in countries with comparable high labour costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment caused by it, government expenditure necessarily increases.
This situation is reinforced by the fact that the entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby replace the overall social and economic damage caused by them.
This situation is generally known, so that specific statistics are unnecessary at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates in the individual economies a situation in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver private capital to their own people without regard to the social consequences.
This is particularly evident in changes in the laws in force.
The aim of these measures is to force one's own population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is done on the one hand by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, on the other hand by the circumcision of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as increasing differences between the rich and the poor.
In Germany there have been public food outlets for the poor for several years now, which are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regular cases in which workers receive such a low wage that the state must increase their income to the minimum of existence.
Such a scandal was also revealed in the case of aid workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU Southern States will undoubtedly go out to the same state where people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level (as was the case in the 19th century), or for a hunger wage on the fringes of society, hoping that at some point private investment capital will flow into the country.
Naturally, this raises the question of where this capital comes from.
If it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or capital remains the same, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or in Africa, workers are actually working for a fraction of European wages.
This is all about Latin America.
Liberal theories and media allege that the state must not participate in its own economy with capital, and that the planned economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital insists firmly on its position that the state must not intervene in the economy.
But then one has to wonder whether private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the entire state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer: Yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual advantage, a legislation in which virtually everything is criminal but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that a Ministry of State, in the absence of finance, commissions private legal entities, closely intertwined with industry, to draft legislation.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer comes from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Apparently, the liberal democracies are now quickly entering a situation, as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic at the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been in disintegration, and the offices were occupied with force.
Against lubricating money, by unlawful encroachment of advantages or with stone and sword.
Corruption grew imperceptibly, and the people went with already bought votes for election" ... "People with character did not apply for offices, so that as a result of this decline the state did not have a consul for eight months" ... "One really began to talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult situation was a sole rule, and that a strong man had to be elected" ...
As it turns out, today’s society, as in ancient times, is founded on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital, by its very nature, is not able to recognize and enforce the advantage for the whole of society.
The result, today as it was then, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites, who are not in the least striving for deeper reforms.
We must therefore seek the cause of the emergence of fascism and communism in the ruthless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today’s perspective, the downfall of these regimes in favor of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already taking place.
Especially catastrophic is the fact that today’s elites face the possible loss of hundreds of thousands of lives in the future, the humanitarian and social disasters we already witness today, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them from older and more recent history, in complete ignorance.
The repeal of the law on charitable works is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under pressure from global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will continue to seek ways to push the social level of the population down.
This trend is therefore system-related.
The only solution is targeted political-social reforms that increase the state’s capital participation in the economy, increase citizens’ influence on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
