The movie Argo: If it's worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had maintained the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent failure in the violent attempt to free the hostages only made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
Debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter’s defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the embassy was occupied, six ambassadors managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, helping them uncover their true identity with an extravagant story – they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for “exfiltration,” Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood’s collaboration.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time, based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic police thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly overstimulated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the office floors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable start to his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor, he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime No Child's Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller city without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film, which does not play in the director's Boston home.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that lifted the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the entrance sequence of the embarrassment of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet still conveys the feeling of confusion and the unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the little he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality - which doesn't always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is turned away by a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat contrived).
The weakness of Argo is its overly broad spread, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and thus they are by far not alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some traction, which is a film that can be watched with some interest, and the design and retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70’s.
However, he awakens enthusiasm only with difficulty.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is alive to this day, and as proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services are, it is sufficient.
