So this is my proposal for the Buchenberg von Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is stored up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small-town retort, which up to now had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian zone and a stately ugly town hall, behind which white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to make a piece of contemporary architecture richer.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural construction in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
First impression: Bookeldorado under cheese bell.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, the true pleasures of space and reading are unlocked when climbing the topography on foot.
The all-glass interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lamps speak the language of a public city square unmistakably.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Normally, the bookshelves are standing along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, and in the middle is a large, dark space that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and pushed the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: In the middle are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology center.
A special delight are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall cladding, sometimes bristling, sometimes ladder railings.
Optics, haptics and smells are foreign.
Even incarcerated architects and civil engineers shake their heads about the unknown building material.
“We wanted to work with recycling materials here,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so, in a Frisian farm, one day we encountered a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a root pad.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts one, two seasons, after which it is ripe for the barrier waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed into four centimeters thick plates for the first time in these quantities.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, resilient material that smells like a new car and a new shoe.
After 105 steps, you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500 meters long walk, you will be rewarded in the literature café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the New Soul
“You wouldn’t believe it, but this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology despite the many glass surfaces,” says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Buchenberg is under a glass fall, even on sunny days, the sun appears only briefly inside.
The wide wooden glue binders, which are located across the glass facade, serve as shade and capture much of the sunlight.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest are fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already ventured the way into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who calls Boekenberg even as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: To open a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal stock.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the library that has not yet been fully stocked – currently 70,000 pieces – are to be filled.
The concept has begun.
The shelves are filled to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which is called the identity foundation in the technical jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
