Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most smelly fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living – not only in Europe, but around the world.
Could the country’s secret of success have anything to do with the local appetite for rather foul-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a bunch of dirty, damp sportswear.
And leave her there for a week.
This is about the nose numbing smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am located in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and this stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is a salt-strewn trout that is fermented in water for up to a year, depending on how stinky you would like your fish.
When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, well, really very captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of Aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works in the local fire station, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "rakfisk general".
People around us eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
“Some people like the Aquavit more than the Rakfisk,” Havard says.
The spirit can displace the smell.
I'll take a few bites.
If you avoid getting the Rakfisk near your nose, it’s not bad – like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a very different, much poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling options and fish was soaked in airtight salt water barrels in autumn.
In the deepest winter he was then taken out after a long fermentation and - undoubtedly with the help of alcohol dampened senses - consumed.
A generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and mainly emigrated to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and a comprehensive healthcare system.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, who was far richer than Norway not so long ago, immigrants flock.
Rakfisk is considered to be something important - an essential, albeit strictly smelling part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the most expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proudly 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t often make it into the world press, and most people don’t seem to mind that.
Here you still hate to call Anders Breivik by name - those racist right-wing extremists who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it refers only to the "July 22 incident".
Norwegians are struggling to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal killings.
The main responsibility for Norway’s present wealth has been the growth of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world since the early 1970s.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes the round trays with mature rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and piercing blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Your English is just like most people here immaculately.
We're not very vociferous, we don't like bragging.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very carefully – a large part of the industry’s revenues are invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the global economic crisis, everyone threw around with money that they didn’t have, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
“As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we are happy,” says Anna.
"And of course eat rakfisk," she adds with careless laughter.
I stand in the snow and prepare for another dish - from Rakfisk I have enough.
Such an elk-citizen is definitely something else. The juicy meat is my mouth.
But in the evening the Stinkfish is again on the menu.
The hotel where I stay is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best - or perhaps the most challenging - fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates with rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here's our points, Havard".
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But maybe it's the strict haze of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces tough start
As Mexico’s future President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares for his inauguration, Will Grant from the BBC analyses the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly poor.
Even on better days, this is an always clogged city, but on Monday a ring of steel was built, which locks off several important traffic routes to the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
However, the goal was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new President Enrique Pena Nieto will take over the leadership of the nation.
He is facing a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderons, Mexico has been able to prove itself economically, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing the violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy with which we can achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. President, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are shared.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, you like to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to him the development of tourism and the construction of the infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built and which represent a great improvement over the fragile, bumpy streets that once existed here.
Plaques with its name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, the PRI.
In particular, as regards security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country urgently needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, the new president lack substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was turned on to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
The bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left on a patch of Brachland near a large landfill in the last two years alone.
During the tenure of Governor Pena Nieto, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico – a statistic that surpasses even that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics Pena Nietos believe that he has at least not adequately addressed the problem of women's murders during his term of office.
But in the worst case, his government closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the run down neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with her tears as she shows me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her life partner.
“When I arrived at her home, it seemed like her body had been washed,” recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the body star had already used.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall and is placed next to a cross with one word: justice.
But this, according to the family, has been denied to her so far.
The authorities treated me as if I were a talker, a troublemaker, a nuggler.
They want you to simply accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and omissions,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidency on Saturday, he also assumes a great deal of responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his term in office.
“I hope he is as president as he was as governor,” said Prime Minister Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of this.
The Prosecutor's Office claims Bradley Manning has not complained about abuse
The prosecutor's office contradicts Bradley Manning's allegations that he has been mistreated in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks to dismiss the charge due to harsh conditions of detention
The liberator of the U.S. Army is accused of squandering thousands of confidential documents
The prosecutor's office on Friday tried to determine that the army-free Bradley Manning - accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history - missed several opportunities to complain about the alleged abuse he suffered in military custody.
At a cross-examination Mannings during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that documents on weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, had no complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to reject the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard jail time - Manning had stated that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as a source of information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out after their meeting with Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been incarcerated from July 2010 to April 2011 under increased conditions of detention.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had assessed the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the establishment as "very professional" overall.
The forms, according to Fein, contained no complaints about abuse, although officials had asked Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they were dealing with them, but they had not been recorded.
“They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) ‘No problems’, and that didn’t necessarily mean I didn’t say anything at all,” Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to examine the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to have his observation status downgraded to “prevention of injuries.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status — which is one stage under the threat of suicide — to his and to the protection of others.
“I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and get rid of the observational status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my opinion,” Manning said.
Manning said on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the prison of Quantico Naval Base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had become unconscious due to the heat.
Not knowing what was going on with him or in the outside world was burdensome.
“My world shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together,” Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
When he was moved to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without society.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion because the day was forbidden to sleep or just lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated into his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards couldn’t see his face anymore, they woke him up so that he turned back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison of Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an accusation he had raised in his statement on Thursday – so he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had stated that he had never had the opportunity to envelop himself with his blanket during this count.
At Friday's interview, Manning stated that he had shut down a command from his guard to drop the blanket he could have covered, but admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked the previous night, trying to show an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the officer that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and drastically reduce his detention rate should he be convicted in his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses, while other charges, which are considered too extreme, are to be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecutor’s office is expected to justify the terms of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning was detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all prisoners detained in Quantico under the highest security measures.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful disclosure of intelligence information on the Internet, the transmission of national defense information and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty in all charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants – they call on them to remember difficult times, he says.
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at passport control when inconsistency spread within me.
Signs referred to two queues: one for "Mexicans" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure of which one to go to.
I grew up in central California and was called "Mexicans" all my life.
An ethnic shortcoming - just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York "Italians".
Later, I decided to call myself "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home, there was no need for shortcuts or hyphens.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I won’t let go of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda included all the issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to stay in Mexico rather than emigrate to the United States.
He wants to unite with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue the war in Mexico against the drug cartels, even though he did not mention any details in this regard.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the country's leadership under a rifle to leave them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be missed.
So once a U.S. government official has even the mildest criticism of Mexico, complaints are heard in the Mexican press and among the country’s elites about how Americans are oppressing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezumas go on the path of war.
And yet, Mexico’s biggest challenge is in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentments?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person — perhaps a parent or grandparent — got no chance in Mexico and emigrated to the north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may have lived the American dream, attended good schools, and got good jobs, we must never lose sight of the American dream that we live - not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
Moreover, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial to a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In your opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have left.
And then we wouldn't be trapped behind the silk curtain - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans, because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are – and Mexican Americans are taking this awry to them.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know have the feeling that they don’t belong to either one country or the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the education bourgeoisie want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well.
That won't happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unequal distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if it is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico one and a half centuries ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge about how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "mexican" than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such a hope in the germ.
In the midst of the usual indebtedness, countless buildings were laid in rubble and ashes, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed - and for the first time, rockets from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem have been struck.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not - Palestinians and Israelis have become part of these turmoils.
Maybe this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate situation could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems anything but appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the cease-fire agreed on 21 November, this week’s fighting has strengthened the hard-fought on both sides.
Hamas’s leaders, the Islamist movement that has been controlling the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, despite the fact that its group itself had to face heavy losses.
Although several Hamas leaders have been killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are incarcerated in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has not yet succeeded in destroying Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And Hamas leaders could come to the conclusion that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to attract powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has seized for the Hamas party – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Hailing Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has the power to cross Syria, where rebels could face an increasingly Islamist imprint on Bashar Assad’s overthrow, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Mursi in Egypt - the most populous and important Arab country by far - on the southern flank of Israel has changed the region's balance sustainably.
Hosni Mubarak, the Laizist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is veiled with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor who cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
From a military standpoint, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, Iron Dome, has proved itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more peacefully.
From a diplomatic point of view, the United States remains steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers, not least thanks to the lockdowns that extend into the West Bank and thus into the main part of any Palestinian state, protecting the Jewish settlements, which have been declared illegal under international law, but are still being expanded.
Netanyahu is in good hands, and his Likud party has joined an even more militant group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these insidious Palestinians also embarrass and leave them a state of their own?
If they were in fact in control of the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire rockets just like their counterparts in the Gaza Strip?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to assert themselves, but the Arab Spring could make them a dash through the bill.
Even if the Islamists, now in power in Egypt and in other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense seat is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economy.
The fact that the pragmatic President Mursi met with Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder barrel that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli-occupied areas, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Suppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population this situation will only intensify.
Bloody missions to repress Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is that represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states in which Israel cedes territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, along with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms shipments to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by land swaps and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also move Hamas and Fatah to an agreement.
This would be done more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the upcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must help move Israel to negotiations.
During his first term in office, he missed the idea of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he was equally averse to participation.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a major interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian law on uniform cigarette packaging comes into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and babies and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small print, is from next Saturday.
Australia has introduced the world’s most stringent tobacco packaging regulations.
The Australian government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco consumption.
The government is assuming that studies that have shown that people who have not started smoking at 26 are not likely to start smoking afterwards, with a 99% chance.
"You can already see in children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," said Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, quoting studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will only have a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It said that the laws would favour black market trading, leading to cheaper and more easily accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the intolerable packaging has risen enormously since the companies British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed two months ago at the Supreme Australian Court with their challenge to the laws.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units in wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
For us, this is a good business.
According to experts, the catch in the popularity of social media lies with exactly the population group to which the plan is aimed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most retailers to stop putting cigarettes out in stores, and now tobacco advertising has been switched to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Anyone who markets tobacco and has only a small area left to promote their products doesn’t get around the Internet,” says Becky Freeman, a researcher in healthcare at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has seen an increase in reviews of brands written by “normal people.”
You have to ask yourself: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that they even record a video for it – or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry instead of marketing focuses on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations – those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, although none of the countries engage in major trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected for mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to issue photographic warnings in 2001.
These have now been expanded to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures do not affect me.
I just ignore them.
“You just take a tip and put the box away,” says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box where a photo is printed with a mouth tumor.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd stop, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the tobacco trade "King of the Pack" in downtown Sydney, says the uniform packaging has made filling his shelves more difficult.
“I used to take an hour to sort a delivery, now I need four,” Yu says.
"The government should have simply banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said okay, that's it, we're closing down," he added visibly infuriated.
In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored sometimes
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane fell out due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to make a few thoughts boring.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty annoying – even when books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are leading boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us – and our children – to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us today are almost constantly staring at one or the other screen, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
So should we welcome the boredom with open arms?
Yeah, yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011), doesn't see that.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
The house walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York, Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After long reading of research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of " wanting to do a satisfying job but not being able to do it".
As a result, boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in a “disruption of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly.”
This can make boredom sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their surroundings or in the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re boring, even when we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of boredom under the aspect of attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume in front of a magazine.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content, others listened to it at low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they felt more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could find no reason for it and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
If you’re trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, disruption of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
If, on the other hand, you perform a monotonous activity - "just like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that hemmings and crayons, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people more physically alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to hug around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” said Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a roaring speaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale of boredom susceptibility" in the 1980s.
On the scale there are statements such as "Many things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more often bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida – especially in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a rather tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of the adults at school and doing homework were bored, while 23% said they were bored when they weren’t in school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know if the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is certain that “youth is considered particularly boring,” mainly because children and teenagers have no major influence on their daily lives.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and gamble or drugs to relieve them – studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity, which is Professor Vodanovich’s opinion, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else,” said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
If you’re bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you’ll be happy.
Television, however, can cause feelings of happiness in the short term, but they will evaporate again in the long term.
So, if you give your bored child an iPad, you can take it away from boredom, but it has not learned to entertain or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, “Self-control transfers from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we see them too critical.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from constant activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we should be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to turn off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it's hard to get busy once the noise is muted."
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
A 19-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco stands trial in southeastern Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in this state: possession of a few fewer marijuana chunks and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving a car in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was charged with possession of drugs and drug equipment — cavalry crimes, each with a $100 penalty — and received a court date.
"We are treated like criminals," Orozco said.
But is he also one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the response to hundreds of smaller drug offences depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of misdemeanors surrounding marijuana are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
Police authorities are no longer tracking adults over the age of 21 for possession to a small extent, which is permitted by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the next few weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s more conservative districts have announced that they will continue to pursue existing marijuana crimes and are still citing people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, agree to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their communities.
“This situation is evolving so fast that I don’t know what’s going to happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, Aurora Police Chief, located east of Denver.
And regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug – and have a deadline until 1 December 2013.
In Washington, Colorado is believed to be ahead of most states in the regulation of marijuana, where the drug was legalized for medical purposes and self-consumption.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well-suited for orientation,” said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State’s liquor regulator.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we can follow,” he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, comes into force on December 6, making it the end point of a grey area in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but the possession is legalized.
And uncomfortable practical issues need to be clarified at this time – for example, how the state’s provision of “appropriate access” to licensed marijuana is to be agreed upon with the banning of cannabis businesses around 300 meters around schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his Aurora staff stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses in people over the age of 21, and that the police would "from now on" not seek criminal charges for these offenses.
Chief Oates added that the police will continue to enforce urban regulations regulating growers of medical marijuana and drug traffickers will continue to be prosecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck has a stricter view.
After the vote, he stated that his authority would continue to track cases of marijuana possession, mainly to move consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people have to answer for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have also been charged with other crimes.
“Our authority has a duty to prosecute violations involving crimes at the time of the crime,” Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are ambiguous even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, no longer show adults for possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all outstanding property proceedings.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time enforcing the right until it changes," he says.
Although 55% of voters in Colorado supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile personal consumption of marijuana with the complexities of government and legal system.
And the conflicting reactions throughout the state encouraged a profound split among local officials in view of the great green experiment.
District attorneys are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney who represents marijuana victims in court and acts locally as a spokesman for the national organization for the reform of marijuana laws.
“They have spent such a large part of their lives pursuing individuals for criminal prosecution that they still cannot accept legalization,” he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana such as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are treated as national sample cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an age of legal sales, they are also waiting nervously for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a crime.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will yield.
Despite several sensational arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former Obama administration drug policy adviser, believes that while law enforcement officials are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of drugs, they are likely to be robbing themselves of legal, state-regulated marijuana business under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not even waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local municipal administrations approved moratoriums for new marijuana businesses, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, decided on a six-month ban, which is likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, member of the city council.
Our community voted against this change of law.
We are guided by what the community has chosen, not by what the state has chosen.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only university students of today are being attacked for their views
It has always been my dream to have a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended that university, which I once considered to be the world’s greatest temple of knowledge, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization – free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of entering Worscester College at the end of the eighties – where I had planned to study history – I had packed my suitcases again and thus brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down in tears.
My friends were confused.
In the Evening Standard it was said that I would have gone because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A N Wilson said that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I was harassed for one reason only - a reason that seemed so narrower and crueler in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my now deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatchers and I advocated the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to current reports, a new generation of students of moderate rights suffers from similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for equal rights protection that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College’s Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are “often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable” due to their political views.
They demand a seat on their college’s equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Her situation was exacerbated by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which Tories portrayed as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
Among other things, this was shown by graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University’s conservative student association, who rode in a Rolls-Royce and wore a silver suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered “beneficial for introducing higher tuition fees.”
Luke Black, 20-year-old vice president of the University of Nottingham’s conservative student association, said in a Sunday newspaper: “There is a growing left-wing tendency at universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other."
Samuel Roberts, 21 and a history student in Corpus Christi who initiated the application for greater protection, believes such a climate is "unpleasant". 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, designated president of Oxford's conservative student association, says she has observed a growing rejection of students of moderate rights among JCR members.
“This poses a danger to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members,” she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred for the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university had voted not to award Margaret Thatcher – a former student – an honorary degree due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even frightened Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of the future events.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the mocking of Tory students, but even participated with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, the privatization and the rejection of the government of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wooden rooms of the Tutorium.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English, and I wasn’t prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled into it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like a cake dough, and pretty ugly.
"Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students chirped.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I suggest they take a few French lessons in their spare time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt murmured.
I returned to my room with a hanging head.
That night, I was sitting in college alone at dinner, when someone slightly tipped me on my shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is what it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is being harassed.
It's already bad enough for me, but they know that your father Margaret Thatcher is close, so it'll be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub, I later tried to change my mind.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs. Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A beginner in philosophy, politics and economics, who had ironically attended Eton College, a conservative, said to me, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.”
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked.
They beat each other, don't they?
I felt like homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever succeed in living a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years before me extended before my spiritual eye to a purgatory of awe and isolation.
The only tutor who openly recognized himself as Tory was Norman Stone, professor of contemporary history, who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for them.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and small-minded, and rejected it for his Marxist-Determinist perspective on history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I started commuting between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreamy tower peaks.
Even my communist friends always showed perfect manners.
His wet eyes were dimmed.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance became weaker.
One of my male friends, also Tory supporters, had given up on the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, in which another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Even though I was secretly torn from shame, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to a "brainwashing" and called them "old sluts."
The relief lasted only a short time.
It was my father who hit the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was closed.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my asses gave up.
When they left, I grabbed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You can call me a crying swallow.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
