The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the Indonesian volcano’s carriers risk their lives and health when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by getting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulfur-containing gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping paths made of stone.
Although it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to rise at turtle speed, keeping the balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the slopes of Kawah Ijen.
The Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 Eurocents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
When they arrive at the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who has been exploiting the volcanic deposits since 1960 and (never better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocents) for every kilo of sulfur.
This is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
“Since we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route,” explains Anto, who usually makes three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours, after which it is completely finished, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a meserable reward for such an almost inhuman effort, however, is the triple of what he would earn with field work.
“The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day at the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high,” explains the bearer, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
